<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="40" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,152,439]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,337,226,252]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is the Latin adjetive 
<emphasis box="[826,888,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">nigro</emphasis>
meaning “dark” and 
<emphasis box="[1142,1238,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">capitata</emphasis>
meaning “head” referring to the dark coloration of the head, which is uncommon in 
<taxonomicName box="[939,1111,264,289]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Desmopachria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[939,1111,264,289]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">Desmopachria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,152,439]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,431,301,327]" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
This new species is not placed in any group. The male genitalia possess some similarities with the 
<emphasis box="[392,514,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">portmania</emphasis>
group 
<emphasis box="[597,662,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="40">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Miller, K. B." box="[670,829,338,364]" journalOrPublisher="The Coleopteristis Bulletin" pageId="7" pageNumber="40" pagination="219 - 240" part="55" refString="Miller, K. B. (2001) Description of new species of Desmopachria Babington (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae: Hydroporini: Hyphidrini) with a reassessment of the subgenera and species groups and a synopsis of the species. The Coleopteristis Bulletin, 55 (2), 219 - 240." title="Description of new species of Desmopachria Babington (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae: Hydroporini: Hyphidrini) with a reassessment of the subgenera and species groups and a synopsis of the species" type="journal article" year="2001">Miller (2001)</bibRefCitation>
in the curved form of the aedeagus and in the setae of the parameres, however the bifid base of the aedeagus and the absence of bifurcation on the prosternal process excludes it from this group.
</paragraph>
